Multi-cloud Performance Analysis

This experiment evalutes the performance of two multi-cloud APIs - jclouds and libclouds - compared to AWS and Azure APIs for storage service. This document summarises results of this experiment and provides R commands used to produce the analysis.

1. Preliminary Procedures

These procedures consists of importing the data set into the R environment, activating extras libraries, and organising data for performing analyses.

1.1. Importing dataset

The original dataset consists of 11 variables and 39.722 observations, organised in: - Platform; - Language; - API; - Filesize; and - Activity.

For each of these variables, it was collected: - CPU time (ms); - Memory (KB); and - Latency (ms)

# Setting up current directory
setwd("~/Google Drive/Production/Empirical research/2016 - 02_06 - Performance multi-clouds/Data Analysis")

2.2. Is there any correlation between performance (cputime) and filesize?

correlations.matrix <- matrix(nrow = 16, ncol = 6)

activity.var <- "download"
index <- 1

for (activity in 1:2) {
  language.var <- "java"
  
  for (language in 1:2) {
    platform.var <- "aws"
    
    for (platform in 1:2) {
      api.var <- "multicloud"  

      for (api in 1:2) {
        x <- subset (
              dataset.raw,
              activity == activity.var &
              language == language.var &
              platform == platform.var &
              api == api.var
            )$cputime
        
        y <- subset (
              dataset.raw,
              activity == activity.var &
              language == language.var &
              platform == platform.var &
              api == api.var
            )$filesize
        
          cor.result <- cor.test( # Calculates spearman's correlation
            x = x,
            y = y,
            method = "spearman"
            )
          
          correlations.matrix[index, 1] <- activity.var
          correlations.matrix[index, 2] <- language.var
          correlations.matrix[index, 3] <- platform.var
          correlations.matrix[index, 4] <- api.var
          correlations.matrix[index, 5] <- round (cor.result$estimate, digits = 3)
          correlations.matrix[index, 6] <- cor.result$p.value
          index <- index + 1

          api.var <- "native"
      }
      
      platform.var <- "azure"
    }
    
    language.var <- "python"
  }
  
  activity.var <- "upload"
}

df <- as.data.frame(correlations.matrix)
names (df) <- c("Activity", "Language", "Platform", "API", "rho", "p value")

2.3. Is there any difference between activities?

descriptive.statistics <- matrix(nrow = 16, ncol = 11)


api.var <- "multicloud"  

index <- 1

for (api in 1:2) {
  language.var <- "java"
  
  for (language in 1:2) {
    platform.var <- "aws"
    
    for (platform in 1:2) {
      activity.var <- "download" 

      for (activity in 1:2) {
        dataset.temp <- subset (
              dataset.raw,
              activity == activity.var &
              language == language.var &
              platform == platform.var &
              api == api.var
            )
        
          quantile_result <- quantile(dataset.temp$cputime) # Calculates most descriptive statistics
        
          descriptive.statistics[index, 1] <- api.var
          descriptive.statistics[index, 2] <- language.var
          descriptive.statistics[index, 3] <- platform.var
          descriptive.statistics[index, 4] <- activity.var
          descriptive.statistics[index, 5] <- round(quantile_result[[1]], digits = 3) # Min
          descriptive.statistics[index, 6] <- round(quantile_result[[2]], digits = 3) # 1st Quartile
          descriptive.statistics[index, 7] <- round(quantile_result[[3]], digits = 3) # Median
          descriptive.statistics[index, 8] <- round(quantile_result[[4]], digits = 3) # 2nd Quartile
          descriptive.statistics[index, 9] <- round(quantile_result[[5]], digits = 3) # Max
          descriptive.statistics[index, 10] <- round(quantile_result[[4]] - quantile_result[[2]], digits = 3) # Inter quartile
          descriptive.statistics[index, 11] <- round(quantile_result[[5]] - quantile_result[[1]], digits = 3) # Range
          
          index <- index + 1

          activity.var <- "upload"
      }
      
      platform.var <- "azure"
    }
    
    language.var <- "python"
  }
  
  api.var <- "native"
}

inferential.statistics <- matrix(nrow = 8, ncol = 5)

language.var <- "java"
index <- 1

  for (language in 1:2) {
    platform.var <- "aws"
    
    for (platform in 1:2) {
      api.var <- "multicloud"  

      for (api in 1:2) {
        dataset.temp <- subset (
              dataset.raw,
              language == language.var &
              platform == platform.var &
              api == api.var
            )
        
          wilcox.result <- wilcox.test( # Calculates the significance test
            cputime ~ activity, 
            data = dataset.temp,
            mu = 0, 
            paired = FALSE, 
            conf.level = 0.95
          )
          
          inferential.statistics[index, 1] <- language.var
          inferential.statistics[index, 2] <- platform.var
          inferential.statistics[index, 3] <- api.var
          inferential.statistics[index, 4] <- wilcox.result$p.value
          inferential.statistics[index, 5] <- wilcox.result$statistic
        
          index <- index + 1

          api.var <- "native"
      }
      
      platform.var <- "azure"
    }
    
    language.var <- "python"
  }

df <- as.data.frame(inferential.statistics)

# Calculating Vargha & Delaney A effect size

effectSize.matrix <- matrix(nrow = 8, ncol = 4)

language.var <- "java"
index <- 1

  for (language in 1:2) {
    platform.var <- "aws"
    
    for (platform in 1:2) {
      api.var <- "multicloud"  

      for (api in 1:2) {
        dataset.temp <- subset (
              dataset.raw,
              language == language.var &
              platform == platform.var &
              api == api.var
            )
        
          effSize.var <- VD.A ( # Calculates the effect size
            data = dataset.temp,
            cputime ~ activity
          )
        
          effectSize.matrix[index, 1] <- language.var
          effectSize.matrix[index, 2] <- platform.var
          effectSize.matrix[index, 3] <- api.var
          effectSize.matrix[index, 4] <- effSize.var$estimate
        
          index <- index + 1

          api.var <- "native"
      }
      
      platform.var <- "azure"
    }
    
    language.var <- "python"
  }

df <- as.data.frame(effectSize.matrix)
names (df) <- c("Language", "Platform", "API", "A-Measure")
df
##   Language Platform        API         A-Measure
## 1     java      aws multicloud  0.55357802020202
## 2     java      aws     native 0.353298937908497
## 3     java    azure multicloud        0.47510808
## 4     java    azure     native        0.29412152
## 5   python      aws multicloud 0.971527886619425
## 6   python      aws     native        0.68305625
## 7   python    azure multicloud         0.8946136
## 8   python    azure     native        0.53386488

According to the result above, for Java, differences are small for multicloud, but representative for native whereas for Python, differences are greater for multiclouds than native. Conclusion: for cputime, it is important to consider download and upload activities as individual activities because they consume resources differently.

2.4. Are differences between multicloud and native APIs relevant?

significance.cputime.matrix <- matrix(nrow = 8, ncol = 5)

activity.var <- "download"
index <- 1

for (activity in 1:2) {
  language.var <- "java"
  
  for (language in 1:2) {
    platform.var <- "aws"
    
    for (platform in 1:2) {
      dataset.temp <- subset (
              dataset.raw,
              activity == activity.var &
              language == language.var &
              platform == platform.var
            )
      
     wilcox.result <- wilcox.test( # Calculates the statistical significance
        cputime ~ api,
        data = dataset.temp,
        mu = 0,
        paired = FALSE,
        conf.level = 0.95
      )
     
      significance.cputime.matrix[index, 1] <- activity.var
      significance.cputime.matrix[index, 2] <- language.var
      significance.cputime.matrix[index, 3] <- platform.var
      significance.cputime.matrix[index, 4] <- wilcox.result$p.value

3.2. Is there any correlation between performance (memory) and filesize?

correlations.matrix <- matrix(nrow = 16, ncol = 6)

activity.var <- "download"
index <- 1

for (activity in 1:2) {
  language.var <- "java"
  
  for (language in 1:2) {
    platform.var <- "aws"
    
    for (platform in 1:2) {
      api.var <- "multicloud"  

      for (api in 1:2) {
        x <- subset (
              dataset.raw,
              activity == activity.var &
              language == language.var &
              platform == platform.var &
              api == api.var
            )$memory
        
        y <- subset (
              dataset.raw,
              activity == activity.var &
              language == language.var &
              platform == platform.var &
              api == api.var
            )$filesize
        
          cor.result <- cor.test( # Calculates spearman's correlation
            x = x,
            y = y,
            method = "spearman"
            )
          
          correlations.matrix[index, 1] <- activity.var
          correlations.matrix[index, 2] <- language.var
          correlations.matrix[index, 3] <- platform.var
          correlations.matrix[index, 4] <- api.var
          correlations.matrix[index, 5] <- round (cor.result$estimate, digits = 3)
          correlations.matrix[index, 6] <- cor.result$p.value
          index <- index + 1

          api.var <- "native"
      }
      
      platform.var <- "azure"
    }
    
    language.var <- "python"
  }
  
  activity.var <- "upload"
}

df <- as.data.frame(correlations.matrix)

descriptive.statistics <- matrix(nrow = 16, ncol = 11)


api.var <- "multicloud"  

index <- 1

for (api in 1:2) {
  language.var <- "java"
  
  for (language in 1:2) {
    platform.var <- "aws"
    
    for (platform in 1:2) {
      activity.var <- "download" 

      for (activity in 1:2) {
        dataset.temp <- subset (
              dataset.raw,
              activity == activity.var &
              language == language.var &
              platform == platform.var &
              api == api.var
            )
        
          quantile_result <- quantile(dataset.temp$memory) # Calculates most descriptive statistics
        
          descriptive.statistics[index, 1] <- api.var
          descriptive.statistics[index, 2] <- language.var
          descriptive.statistics[index, 3] <- platform.var
          descriptive.statistics[index, 4] <- activity.var
          descriptive.statistics[index, 5] <- round(quantile_result[[1]], digits = 3) # Min
          descriptive.statistics[index, 6] <- round(quantile_result[[2]], digits = 3) # 1st Quartile
          descriptive.statistics[index, 7] <- round(quantile_result[[3]], digits = 3) # Median
          descriptive.statistics[index, 8] <- round(quantile_result[[4]], digits = 3) # 2nd Quartile
          descriptive.statistics[index, 9] <- round(quantile_result[[5]], digits = 3) # Max
          descriptive.statistics[index, 10] <- round(quantile_result[[4]] - quantile_result[[2]], digits = 3) # Inter quartile
          descriptive.statistics[index, 11] <- round(quantile_result[[5]] - quantile_result[[1]], digits = 3) # Range
          
          index <- index + 1

          activity.var <- "upload"
      }
      
      platform.var <- "azure"
    }
    
    language.var <- "python"
  }
  
  api.var <- "native"

inferential.statistics <- matrix(nrow = 8, ncol = 5)

  for (language in 1:2) {

    }

# Calculating Vargha & Delaney A effect size

effectSize.matrix <- matrix(nrow = 8, ncol = 4)

language.var <- "java"
index <- 1

  for (language in 1:2) {
    platform.var <- "aws"
    
    for (platform in 1:2) {
      api.var <- "multicloud"  

      for (api in 1:2) {
        dataset.temp <- subset (
              dataset.raw,
              language == language.var &
              platform == platform.var &
              api == api.var
            )
        
          effSize.var <- VD.A ( # Calculates the effect size
            data = dataset.temp,
            memory ~ activity
          )
        
          effectSize.matrix[index, 1] <- language.var
          effectSize.matrix[index, 2] <- platform.var
          effectSize.matrix[index, 3] <- api.var
          effectSize.matrix[index, 4] <- effSize.var$estimate
        
          index <- index + 1

          api.var <- "native"
      }
      
      platform.var <- "azure"
    }
    
    language.var <- "python"
  }

          descriptive.statistics[index, 10] <- round(quantile_result[[4]] - quantile_result[[2]], digits = 3) # Inter quartile
          descriptive.statistics[index, 11] <- round(quantile_result[[5]] - quantile_result[[1]], digits = 3) # Range

          index <- index + 1

          api.var <- "native"
      }
      
      platform.var <- "azure"
    }
    
    language.var <- "python"
  }

# Calculating Vargha & Delaney A effect size

effectSize.matrix <- matrix(nrow = 8, ncol = 4)

language.var <- "java"
index <- 1

  for (language in 1:2) {
    platform.var <- "aws"
    
    for (platform in 1:2) {
      api.var <- "multicloud"  

      for (api in 1:2) {
        dataset.temp <- subset (
              dataset.raw,
              language == language.var &
              platform == platform.var &
              api == api.var
            )
        
          effSize.var <- VD.A ( # Calculates the effect size
            data = dataset.temp,
            latency ~ activity
          )
        
          effectSize.matrix[index, 1] <- language.var
          effectSize.matrix[index, 2] <- platform.var
          effectSize.matrix[index, 3] <- api.var
          effectSize.matrix[index, 4] <- effSize.var$estimate
        
          index <- index + 1

          api.var <- "native"
      }
      
      platform.var <- "azure"
    }
    
    language.var <- "python"
  }
